  "body": "I'm mostly wondering why we market a lot of variables as private in the Smart Contracts, instead of making them more extensible.\r\n\r\nLet's take AccessControl  for example\r\n```\r\nabstract contract AccessControl is Context, IAccessControl, ERC165 {\r\n    struct RoleData {\r\n        mapping(address => bool) members;\r\n        bytes32 adminRole;\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    mapping(bytes32 => RoleData) private _roles;\r\n    //...\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\nI'd like to build on top of this contract, and provide the ability to create dynamic role. \r\nhowever roles is private, there is no way for me to read the current roles or add to them.\r\n\r\nI can very easily clone the code, but audits are extremely expensive, it would be a lot nicer if Openzepplin has more extensible contracts, so audits for the masses would be easier and cheaper.\r\n",
